Reasoning: 
1. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper deals with the problem of sequential prediction and provides tools to study the minimax value of the associated game. It proposes sequential complexities as extensions of classical statistical learning theory measures to the sequential setting. This makes it highly likely to belong to the Machine Learning sub-category.
2. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper discusses the minimax value of the associated game, which is a concept from game theory. It also proposes new complexity measures to study learning in the sequential setting. These aspects make it likely to belong to the Information Theory sub-category.
3. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper deals with the problem of online learning and proposes a new framework to study the problem. This makes it likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence sub-category.
4. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper proposes new complexity measures to study learning in the sequential setting. This makes it somewhat likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms sub-category.
5. cs.ST (Statistics): The paper proposes new complexity measures to study learning in the sequential setting and provides precise learning guarantees for the problem of sequential prediction. These aspects make it somewhat likely to belong to the Statistics sub-category.
